---
description: Security best practices for Spring Boot web applications — injection prevention, secret handling, auth, and data exposure. Apply to all Java source files.
globs: **/*.java
---

## Injection prevention
- Never concatenate user input into JPQL, SQL, Solr queries, or shell commands
- Use parameterized queries, `@Query` with named parameters, or query builder APIs exclusively
- Validate and sanitize all user input at the controller boundary before it reaches the service layer

## Secrets and credentials
- No secrets, API keys, passwords, or tokens in source code or committed config files
- Use environment variables or a secrets manager (Vault, AWS Secrets Manager) for all credentials
- Exclude credential fields from `toString()`, `@JsonSerialize`, and log output
- Rotate credentials if they are ever logged or committed — treat it as compromised

## Authentication and authorization
- Every endpoint must have an explicit security rule — no implicit open access
- Use method-level security (`@PreAuthorize`) for fine-grained authorization in services
- Never trust client-supplied user IDs — resolve the authenticated principal from `SecurityContextHolder`
- JWT tokens must be validated on every request — signature, expiry, and issuer

## Data exposure
- Response DTOs must never include fields the caller is not authorized to see
- Paginated endpoints must have a maximum page size — never return unbounded results
- Sensitive fields (`password`, `ssn`, `token`, `secret`) must be excluded from all API responses
- Use `@JsonIgnore` or a dedicated response record — not the entity directly

## Spring Security config
- CSRF protection must be enabled for browser-facing endpoints; can be disabled for stateless API-only apps with JWT
- CORS must be explicitly configured — do not use `@CrossOrigin("*")` in production
- `HttpSecurity` config must deny all unmatched requests by default: `.anyRequest().denyAll()`
- Store passwords with `BCryptPasswordEncoder` (strength ≥ 12) — never MD5, SHA-1, or plain text
